Model
=====

As shown in fig. \[fig1\], we consider a stack of lipid membranes composed of a mixture of saturated (S) and unsaturated (U) lipids, modeled via the *stacked 2D Ising model*. Each lipid bilayer has a finite thickness and can be mapped into a 2D Ising model with conserved magnetization corresponding to the average S/U lipid composition. The Hamiltonian of the membrane stack is [@Hoshino15] $$\begin{aligned}
H = & -J \sum_{i, \langle \boldsymbol{\rho}, \boldsymbol{\rho}' \rangle}
S_{i,\boldsymbol{\rho}} S_{i,\boldsymbol{\rho}'}
-J' \sum_{i, \boldsymbol{\rho}}
S_{i,\boldsymbol{\rho}} S_{i+1,\boldsymbol{\rho}},
\label{hamiltonian}\end{aligned}$$ where the spin variable $S_{i,\boldsymbol{\rho}}=\pm 1$ is located at in-plane position $\boldsymbol{\rho}=(x,y)$ of the $i$-th layer along the $z$-direction, and corresponds to a lattice site occupied either by an S or U lipid, respectively.

